The Bank determined the defalcation was a result of unauthorized activities of an employee (non-officer) of the Bank and a single customer's accounts. There do not appear to be any losses which include the involvement of any other employee. The Bank believes that the defalcation does not include any other customer accounts. The appropriate governmental authorities have been notified, and the Bank is cooperating fully with respect to the authorities' investigation. The Bank maintains insurance coverage for this type of risk, with a deductible of $50,000. Management expects that this claim will constitute a covered loss, and will be initiating the claim with the insurance company for recovery within the policy parameters. $332,000 loss was recognized during the 1st quarter 2014.

Under the merger, CBD survived with new shareholders and new management. Buckeye Nation Interim, Inc, was dissolved effective the date of the merger. The merger led to the requirement of using Purchase Accounting for adustments to the balance sheet, as well as the Push Down Accounting Method (see RI m.7 and RI-A 7). Under Purchase Accounting Loan and Lease Losses are effectively eliminated and replaced with Purchase Accounting Credit Component, which acts similar to ALLL. The amount in the Credit Component was $159,000 at 3/31/2014.
